    <text>
        <body>
            <head>152. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d152fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Staff Material, Middle East, Subject File, Box 69,
                    Morocco: 7/77–2/78. Confidential; Priority; <gloss target="#t_Exdis_1"
                        >Exdis</gloss>. Sent for information to Algiers, Nouakchott, Paris, Madrid,
                    and <gloss target="#t_USUN_1">USUN</gloss>. Printed from a copy that was
                    received in the White House Situation Room. Drafted by <persName
                        corresp="recoJB3QsHSMqYcVi">Bishop</persName>; cleared by <persName
                        corresp="reca5rkDYL39quDMP">Sober</persName>; approved by <persName
                        corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">Tarnoff</persName>. (National Archives, RG 59,
                    Central Foreign Policy File, D770478–1129)</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1977-12-23T02:28:00+00:00">December 23, 1977, 0228Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>306028. Subject: Secretary’s Meeting With Moroccan Ambassador.</p>
            <p>1. <persName corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G">Bengelloun</persName>’s principal interest
                in brief meeting December 22 prior departure on consultations was in underlining his
                government’s desire for a U.S. response to its arms request.<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d152fn2">In telegram 223262 to Rabat, September 16, the Department
                    summarized <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Vance</persName>’s September 13
                    meeting with <persName corresp="recCV9Jb6qcb9in9B">Laraki</persName>, during
                    which <persName corresp="recCV9Jb6qcb9in9B">Laraki</persName> presented the
                    Moroccan request. (National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                    P840070–0320, P800020–1617) For the Moroccan list, see Attachment 3 to <ref
                        target="#d222">Document 222</ref>.</note> He said <placeName
                    corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl">Morocco</placeName> counts on U.S. to help it
                maintain regional equilibrium which now upset by <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algerian</placeName> acquisition of <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> weapons both directly from
                Soviets and via <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyans</placeName>. He
                mentioned in this context current visit to Tripoli and Algiers of <placeName
                    corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName> Chief of Staff. Moroccans are
                peaceful, <persName corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G">Bengelloun</persName> insisted, and
                want U.S. arms only to defend their national territory. Moroccans not concerned by
                situation in <placeName corresp="rec8AtlHhYG0QfwTi">Mauritania</placeName> where
                    <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> are helping, but they
                are worried about their vulnerability in the north, near Oujda and the
                Mediterranean. Algerians are unhappy with King’s position on <placeName
                    corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName> and have been attacking him.
                Moroccans are worried about what <persName corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO"
                    >Boumediene</persName> might do. <persName corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G"
                    >Bengelloun</persName> contrasted <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName>’s constructive geopolitical and <placeName
                    corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName> policies with those of
                    <placeName corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> and noted greater
                similarity between Moroccan and Ameri<pb facs="0389" n="368" xml:id="pg_368"/>can
                free political structures than between those of <placeName
                    corresp="recB0DySeLFQaTlMd">Algeria</placeName> and U.S. Stating that <persName
                    corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO">Boumediene</persName> about to visit Arab capitals
                to encourage resistance to <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName>,
                Ambassador concluded that U.S. knows where its friends are.</p>
            <p>2. In responding, <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> said
                U.S. in process of making final decisions on Moroccan request and other <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs> questions.
                U.S. is sensitive to Moroccan needs and sees <placeName corresp="recLpHNCu4qy8XTDl"
                    >Morocco</placeName> playing a constructive geopolitical role. <persName
                    corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> cited President’s reference in
                meeting with Prime Minister <persName corresp="recVY0ablbchyiqhj">Osman</persName>
                to the importance of bilateral <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recsWOnchx3QJo5qE">relations</rs> over and above geopolitical
                    concerns.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d152fn3">See <ref target="#d151"
                        >Document 151</ref>.</note> Asked by <persName corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G"
                    >Bengelloun</persName> if it would be possible to make a final decision on the
                Moroccan arms list prior to the President’s departure on December 29,<note n="4"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d152fn4">
                    <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName> traveled to Warsaw on
                    December 29 for an official visit.</note>
                <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> said he doubted it would
                be. However, he looked forward to seeing <persName corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G"
                    >Bengelloun</persName> again when both return to Washington. <persName
                    corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G">Bengelloun</persName> expressed desire discuss legal
                aspects of Moroccan position. <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu"
                    >Secretary</persName> responded he would welcome opportunity for such an
                exchange as there are elements he does not fully understand.</p>
            <p>3. On <orgName corresp="recejMOrt8OMiixBL">Polisario</orgName> hostages, <persName
                    corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G">Bengelloun</persName> said UNSYG <persName
                    corresp="recO0C3IMJcbbKRcq">Waldheim</persName> had not realized <persName
                    corresp="recFHGSIQJfkdnNvO">Boumediene</persName> had provoked a domestic
                political dispute in <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">France</placeName> by
                allowing <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> Communist Party
                Chief Marchais to announce prospective release. According to <persName
                    corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G">Bengelloun</persName>, <persName
                    corresp="recO0C3IMJcbbKRcq">Waldheim</persName> appreciates Moroccan opposition
                to his involvement but feels he must fulfill his commitment.</p>
            <p>4. <persName corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G">Bengelloun</persName> asked if <persName
                    corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> had any special message to
                convey to King on <placeName corresp="recJAi0OpNdSuYev5">Middle East</placeName>
                which might update whatever was discussed between King and Ambassador <persName
                    corresp="recA8IdpBdqcoGQIf">Anderson</persName> December 20.<note n="5"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d152fn5">
                    <persName corresp="recA8IdpBdqcoGQIf">Anderson</persName> reported on his
                    meeting with the King in telegram 6965 from Rabat, December 22. (National
                    Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, P840076–1294)</note>
                <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> replied that he expects
                meeting on Sunday to make progress but it is unreasonable to believe, as some people
                do, that <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> and <persName
                    corresp="recCEPiHPft0cAFn7">Begin</persName> will resolve all issues in one
                    meeting.<note n="6" place="foot" xml:id="d152fn6">
                    <persName corresp="recCEPiHPft0cAFn7">Begin</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> met at Ismailia on Sunday,
                    December 25.</note>
                <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> said he knows <persName
                    corresp="recCEPiHPft0cAFn7">Begin</persName> is going to <placeName
                    corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> in a reasonable frame of mind, and
                he believes <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> also will be
                reasonable. He expects the meeting will continue the momentum of the peace
                process.</p>
            <p>5. Ambassador expressed King <persName corresp="rec8m8MetQlvwXVeh"
                >Hassan</persName>’s best wishes for Under Secretary <persName
                    corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName>’s recovery. <persName
                    corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">Secretary</persName> voiced his appreciation and
                informed <persName corresp="recOFpSMHldAY7z3G">Bengelloun</persName> that <persName
                    corresp="reclbVMhofbughnCg">Habib</persName> has been taken off critical
                list.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recRM4qiy2MVhNDPu">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Vance</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
